This code throws `FileAlreadyExistsException` for `Files.createDirectories`:
```java
  public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
    Files.createDirectories(Path.of(&quot;A/B&quot;));
    Files.createFile(Path.of(&quot;A/B/C&quot;));

    // throws FileAlreadyExistsException(&quot;A/B/C&quot;)
    Files.createDirectories(Path.of(&quot;A/B/C&quot;));
  }
```

Which is expected behaviour according to the [javadoc](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/19/docs/api/java.base/java/nio/file/Files.html#createDirectories(java.nio.file.Path,java.nio.file.attribute.FileAttribute...)); it failed to create a directory because a file (`C`) with the same name already exists. 

You can handle it by deleting the file provided by [`FileSystemException.getFile()`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/19/docs/api/java.base/java/nio/file/FileSystemException.html#getFile()) and trying `Files.createDirectories` again.


___

However - this code throws `NoSuchFileException`:
```java
  public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
    Files.createDirectories(Path.of(&quot;A/B&quot;));
    Files.createFile(Path.of(&quot;A/B/C&quot;));

    // throws NoSuchFileException(&quot;A/B/C/D&quot;)
    Files.createDirectories(Path.of(&quot;A/B/C/D/E&quot;));
  }
```

Because the parent of `D` is a file. 

You can handle it similarly by deleting the parent of the file provided by `getFile()` and trying `Files.createDirectories` again.

It&#39;s strange because it&#39;s not explained in the javadoc. I would expect the same `FileAlreadyExistsException` as in the first example.

___

Also there&#39;s an inconsistency between the exceptions; `FileAlreadyExistsException.getFile()` uses relative path while `NoSuchFileException.getFile()` uses absolute path. So take that into account when handling the exceptions.

